{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016JGDQm6MaxRdmwWSANacKY","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# NOTE: the interval range format is only used internally.\n     2→\n     3→\n     4→\n     5→#' @title Assert that inputs are correct for interval-based forecast\n     6→#' @description\n     7→#' Function assesses whether the inputs correspond to the\n     8→#' requirements for scoring interval-based forecasts.\n     9→#' @param lower Input to be checked. Should be a numeric vector of size n that\n    10→#'   holds the predicted value for the lower bounds of the prediction intervals.\n    11→#' @param upper Input to be checked. Should be a numeric vector of size n that\n    12→#'   holds the predicted value for the upper bounds of the prediction intervals.\n    13→#' @param interval_range Input to be checked. Should be a vector of size n that\n    14→#'   denotes the interval range in percent. E.g. a value of 50 denotes a\n    15→#'   (25%, 75%) prediction interval.\n    16→#' @importFrom cli cli_warn cli_abort\n    17→#' @inherit document_assert_functions params return\n    18→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    19→assert_input_interval <- function(observed, lower, upper, interval_range) {\n    20→\n    21→  assert(check_numeric_vector(observed, min.len = 1))\n    22→  n <- length(observed)\n    23→  assert(check_numeric_vector(lower, len = n))\n    24→  assert(check_numeric_vector(upper, len = n))\n    25→  assert(\n    26→    check_numeric_vector(interval_range, len = 1, lower = 0, upper = 100),\n    27→    check_numeric_vector(interval_range, len = n, lower = 0, upper = 100)\n    28→  )\n    29→\n    30→  diff <- upper - lower\n    31→  diff <- diff[!is.na(diff)]\n    32→  if (any(diff < 0)) {\n    33→    cli_abort(\n    34→      c(\n    35→        \"!\" = \"All values in `upper` need to be greater than or equal to\n    36→        the corresponding values in `lower`\"\n    37→      )\n    38→    )\n    39→  }\n    40→  if (any(interval_range > 0 & interval_range < 1, na.rm = TRUE)) {\n    41→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n    42→    cli_warn(\n    43→      c(\n    44→        \"!\" = \"Found interval ranges between 0 and 1. Are you sure that's\n    45→        right? An interval range of 0.5 e.g. implies a (49.75%, 50.25%)\n    46→        prediction interval.\",\n    47→        \"i\" = \"If you want to score a (25%, 75%) prediction interval, set\n    48→        `interval_range = 50`.\"\n    49→      ),\n    50→      .frequency = \"once\",\n    51→      .frequency_id = \"small_interval_range\"\n    52→    )\n    53→    #nolint end\n    54→  }\n    55→  return(invisible(NULL))\n    56→}\n    57→\n    58→\n    59→#' @title Check that inputs are correct for interval-based forecast\n    60→#' @inherit assert_input_interval params description\n    61→#' @inherit check_input_sample return description\n    62→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    63→check_input_interval <- function(observed, lower, upper, interval_range) {\n    64→  result <- check_try(\n    65→    assert_input_interval(observed, lower, upper, interval_range)\n    66→  )\n    67→  return(result)\n    68→}\n    69→\n    70→\n    71→#' @title Interval score\n    72→#'\n    73→#' @description\n    74→#' Proper Scoring Rule to score quantile predictions, following Gneiting\n    75→#' and Raftery (2007). Smaller values are better.\n    76→#'\n    77→#' The score is computed as\n    78→#'\n    79→#' \\deqn{\n    80→#' \\textrm{score} = (\\textrm{upper} - \\textrm{lower}) + \\frac{2}{\\alpha}(\\textrm{lower}\n    81→#'  - \\textrm{observed}) *\n    82→#' \\mathbf{1}(\\textrm{observed} < \\textrm{lower}) +\n    83→#' \\frac{2}{\\alpha}(\\textrm{observed} - \\textrm{upper}) *\n    84→#' \\mathbf{1}(\\textrm{observed} > \\textrm{upper})\n    85→#' }{\n    86→#' score = (upper - lower) + 2/alpha * (lower - observed) *\n    87→#' 1(observed < lower) + 2/alpha * (observed - upper) *\n    88→#' 1(observed > upper)\n    89→#' }\n    90→#' where \\eqn{\\mathbf{1}()}{1()} is the indicator function and\n    91→#' indicates how much is outside the prediction interval.\n    92→#' \\eqn{\\alpha}{alpha} is the decimal value that indicates how much is outside\n    93→#' the prediction interval.\n    94→#'\n    95→#' To improve usability, the user is asked to provide an interval range in\n    96→#' percentage terms, i.e. interval_range = 90 (percent) for a 90 percent\n    97→#' prediction interval. Correspondingly, the user would have to provide the\n    98→#' 5% and 95% quantiles (the corresponding alpha would then be 0.1).\n    99→#' No specific distribution is assumed, but the interval has to be symmetric\n   100→#' around the median (i.e you can't use the 0.1 quantile\n   101→#' as the lower bound and the 0.7 quantile as the upper bound).\n   102→#' Non-symmetric quantiles can be scored using the function [quantile_score()].\n   103→#'\n   104→#' @param lower Vector of size n with the prediction for the lower quantile\n   105→#'   of the given interval range.\n   106→#' @param upper Vector of size n with the prediction for the upper quantile\n   107→#'   of the given interval range.\n   108→#' @param interval_range Numeric vector (either a single number or a vector of\n   109→#'   size n) with the range of the prediction intervals. For example, if you're\n   110→#'   forecasting the 0.05 and 0.95 quantile, the interval range would be 90.\n   111→#'   The interval range corresponds to \\eqn{(100-\\alpha)/100}, where\n   112→#'   \\eqn{\\alpha}{alpha} is the decimal value that indicates how much is outside\n   113→#'   the prediction interval (see e.g. Gneiting and Raftery (2007)).\n   114→#' @param separate_results Logical. If `TRUE` (default is `FALSE`), then the\n   115→#'   separate parts of the interval score (dispersion penalty, penalties for\n   116→#'   over- and under-prediction get returned as separate elements of a list).\n   117→#'   If you want a `data.frame` instead, simply call [as.